{[show S]This is a Soloway jump shift auction: opener has a one-suiter and responder makes a strong jump in a new suit, announcing slam interest from the first round. The partnership's job is to confirm controls and a trump fit, then climb only as high as the keycards allow.
[BID 1D] ⟦You have a sound opening hand with no five-card major, so open your longest suit. 1\D shows an opening hand of 12+ points and at least four diamonds, and leaves the most room to describe the hand on the next round.⟧ This jump to 2\H is the Soloway jump shift: a game force with slam interest, about 17+ points, four or more controls, and a good suit. Your partner promises a strong hand and a real heart suit, telling partner to start investigating slam.
[BID 3H] ⟦Raising responder's suit shows three-card support and a willingness to cooperate toward slam. You set hearts as trumps so the partnership can stop guessing strain and turn to counting keycards.⟧ With trumps agreed and slam in the air, 4NT is Roman Keycard Blackwood. Your partner asks for the number of keycards — the four aces plus the trump king — so the partnership can judge whether all the controls are present.
[BID 5C] ⟦This step answers the keycard ask, showing the agreed number of aces-plus-trump-king. You give the precise count so partner can add it to your own holding and place the contract.⟧ This continuation is a follow-up ask in the keycard structure, checking for the trump queen or a further control. Your partner keeps the slam investigation going rather than guessing.
[BID 5S] ⟦The answer here confirms the missing card the partnership needed to hear about. You round out the picture so partner can count twelve tricks with confidence.⟧ With all the keycards accounted for, your partner bids the small slam in the agreed trump suit. The Soloway sequence has done its work: a strong responding hand and a fitting opener combine for a sound 6\H.
[BID Pass] ⟦You pass; 6\H is the final contract.⟧
[show NS]North's jump shift showed a strong hand with a good suit and real slam interest, and South's 1\D opener with the heart fit and useful aces filled the gaps. The keycard exchange confirmed the partnership held everything needed, landing a comfortable heart slam.}
