{[show S]A Soloway jump shift starts with a strong hand and a good suit opposite partner's opening. Here opener shows a long major after the strong jump, and the partnership uses keycard Blackwood to settle the right slam.
[BID 1D] ⟦You have a sound opening hand with no five-card major, so open the longer minor. 1\D shows at least four diamonds and a normal opening, leaving room for partner to describe a big hand.⟧ This jump shift to 2\S is forcing to game with slam interest — roughly 17+ points, four or more controls, and a strong suit. Your partner announces the power and a real spade suit, asking opener to keep the auction alive toward slam.
[BID 3D] ⟦Rebidding the opened suit shows extra length and no immediate fit for partner's spades. You clarify the shape so the partnership knows diamonds are long while spades wait to be supported.⟧ Now opener belatedly raises, showing three-card spade support after first describing the diamond length. Your partner confirms the fit, agreeing spades as trumps so slam exploration can proceed.
[BID 4N] ⟦With spades agreed, 4NT is Roman Keycard Blackwood. You ask for keycards — the four aces and the trump king — to find out whether the partnership is missing any controls before committing to slam.⟧ This step answers the keycard ask with the precise count, including any trump-queen information. Your partner reports the controls so partner can add them up and choose the level.
[BID 6S] ⟦Knowing the keycards are present, you bid the small slam in the agreed trump suit. The strong spade jump shift and opener's eventual support combine for a sound 6\S.⟧
