{[show S]A Soloway jump shift promises a strong hand and a good suit, but the partnership still has to find the best strain. Here opener rebids the minor, then offers notrump — and responder must judge whether to insist on the solid suit or accept the notrump game.
[BID 1D] ⟦You have a sound opener with no five-card major, so open the long diamond suit. 1\D shows at least four diamonds and 12+ points.⟧ This jump shift to 2\H is game-forcing with slam interest — roughly 17+ points, four or more controls, and a strong suit. Your partner shows a powerful hand built around real hearts.
[BID 3D] ⟦Rebidding diamonds shows extra length there and no immediate three-card heart fit. You describe the shape so the partnership can decide between hearts, diamonds, and notrump.⟧ Returning to hearts shows a self-sufficient suit good enough to play opposite a doubleton. Your partner suggests hearts as the trump strain rather than leaving it to partner's three diamonds.
[BID 3N] ⟦This is a close, judgment call. Opener bids 3NT to offer the notrump game with stoppers and a flattish hand, and passing it is defensible. But with a self-sufficient suit, raising to 4\H to play in the solid major is the natural home and the alternative the partnership should weigh.
⟧
[show NS]North's strong jump shift wanted to play in the major, and South's notrump-oriented hand with stoppers offered 3NT instead. Both spots make, so this was a genuine judgment between the safe notrump game and the natural heart game — a good reminder that a solid suit usually prefers to be trumps.}
